    <item>
      <title>Scout Motors’ new pickup and SUV EVs will start at “under $60,000”</title>
      <author>
          Jonathan M. Gitlin
        </author>
      <link>https://arstechnica.com/cars/2024/10/scout-motors-new-pickup-and-suv-evs-will-start-at-under-60000/</link>
      <comments>https://arstechnica.com/cars/2024/10/scout-motors-new-pickup-and-suv-evs-will-start-at-under-60000/#comments</comments>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">224cd9496b340543a69c4fdea533867c5f78dd3a</guid>
      <pubDate>Thu, 24 Oct 2024 22:30:16 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;       The Terra pickup and Traveler SUV will be built in South Carolina in 2027.     &lt;/p&gt;&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img width="1881" height="891" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Terra-and-Traveler-Concepts-1-scaled-e1729789684543.jpg" class="intro-image" alt="A pair of electric off-roaders seen in a meadow with mountains in the background" loading="eager" decoding="async" fetchpriority="high" srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Terra-and-Traveler-Concepts-1-scaled-e1729789684543.jpg 1881w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Terra-and-Traveler-Concepts-1-scaled-e1729789684543-300x142.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Terra-and-Traveler-Concepts-1-scaled-e1729789684543-640x303.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Terra-and-Traveler-Concepts-1-scaled-e1729789684543-768x364.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Terra-and-Traveler-Concepts-1-scaled-e1729789684543-1536x728.jpg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Terra-and-Traveler-Concepts-1-scaled-e1729789684543-980x464.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Terra-and-Traveler-Concepts-1-scaled-e1729789684543-1440x682.jpg 1440w" sizes="(max-width: 1881px) 100vw, 1881px" /&gt;&lt;figcaption&gt;       The Scout Terra (left) and Traveler (right) are a pair of new electric off-roaders from the reborn brand, now owned by VW.                &lt;span class="caption-credit mt-2 whitespace-nowrap text-xs"&gt;           Credit:                       Scout Motors                    &lt;/span&gt;           &lt;/figcaption&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;                                                         &lt;aside class="pullbox sidebar fullwidth"&gt;Scout provided flights from Washington to Nashville and accommodation so Ars could attend the reveal. Ars does not accept paid editorial content.&lt;/aside&gt; &lt;p&gt;NASHVILLE, Tenn.—Today, the reborn Scout Motors showed off a pair of new electric vehicles that revives the long-dormant maker of trucks and SUVs. Originally owned by International Harvester, Scout now belongs to Volkswagen Group, which decided to use it to create a new American-made brand for off-road-capable vehicles.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;figure class="ars-img-shortcode id-2058193 align-fullwidth"&gt;     &lt;div&gt;                         &lt;img decoding="async" width="2560" height="1707" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Terra-Concept-3-scaled.jpg" class="fullwidth full" alt="A Scout Terra pickup seen in profile" srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Terra-Concept-3-scaled.jpg 2560w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Terra-Concept-3-300x200.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Terra-Concept-3-640x427.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Terra-Concept-3-768x512.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Terra-Concept-3-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Terra-Concept-3-2048x1365.jpg 2048w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Terra-Concept-3-980x653.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Terra-Concept-3-1440x960.jpg 1440w" sizes="(max-width: 2560px) 100vw, 2560px"&gt;                   &lt;/div&gt;                   &lt;figcaption&gt;           &lt;div class="caption mt-1 inline-flex flex-row items-stretch gap-1 text-lg leading-tight text-gray-300"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-icon bg-[left_top_5px] w-[10px] shrink-0"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-content"&gt;       The Terra is a much less aggressive-looking pickup than you might find at one of the Big Three domestic automakers... or Tesla for that matter.                &lt;span class="caption-credit mt-2 whitespace-nowrap text-xs"&gt;           Credit:                       Scout Motors                    &lt;/span&gt;           &lt;/div&gt;   &lt;/div&gt;         &lt;/figcaption&gt;             &lt;/figure&gt;  &lt;p&gt;The first of these will be the Traveler SUV and Terra pickup truck, due to go into production in 2027. Despite VW's &lt;a href="https://arstechnica.com/cars/2024/06/vw-invests-5b-into-rivian-signaling-deep-tech-ties-and-collaborations/"&gt;recent investment&lt;/a&gt; in Rivian, these are all-new, clean-sheet designs with a platform unique to Scout designed in Michigan, a platform that uses a body-on-frame construction with either purely electric or range-extended powertrains.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Scout says that pricing for the Terra and Traveler should start at "under $60,000," or "as low as $50,000 with available incentives" for the entry-level models, which are due to go into production at a new factory north of Columbia, South Carolina, in 2027.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;div class="ars-lightbox align-fullwidth my-5"&gt;&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img decoding="async" width="640" height="427" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Traveler-Concept-2-640x427.jpg" class="ars-gallery-image" alt="A Scout Traveler SUV seen head-on" loading="lazy" aria-labelledby="caption-2058197" srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Traveler-Concept-2-640x427.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Traveler-Concept-2-300x200.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Traveler-Concept-2-768x512.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Traveler-Concept-2-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Traveler-Concept-2-2048x1365.jpg 2048w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Traveler-Concept-2-980x653.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Traveler-Concept-2-1440x960.jpg 1440w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px"&gt;&lt;figcaption&gt;       The horizontal daylight running lights call back to the Scout II SUV.               &lt;div class="ars-gallery-caption-credit"&gt;Credit:                        Scout Motors                   &lt;/div&gt;           &lt;/figcaption&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img decoding="async" width="640" height="365" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Terra-concept-1-640x365.jpg" class="ars-gallery-image" alt="The front of a Scout Terra pickup truck" loading="lazy" aria-labelledby="caption-2058194" srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Terra-concept-1-640x365.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Terra-concept-1-300x171.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Terra-concept-1-768x438.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Terra-concept-1-1536x876.jpg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Terra-concept-1-2048x1167.jpg 2048w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Terra-concept-1-980x559.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Terra-concept-1-1440x821.jpg 1440w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px"&gt;&lt;figcaption&gt;       Scout says that 80 percent of repairs can be made in the field.                &lt;div class="ars-gallery-caption-credit"&gt;Credit:                        Scout Motors                   &lt;/div&gt;           &lt;/figcaption&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;/div&gt;  &lt;p&gt;"The original core idea—rugged, versatile vehicles capable of off-road adventure and family duty—is more relevant than ever," said Scott Keogh, president and CEO of Scout Motors. "We couldn’t be prouder to revitalize this iconic American brand, create thousands of American jobs, and put American ingenuity back to work."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The tech specs—at least those Scout has shared with Ars—are encouraging. The electric powertrain operates at 800 V and can fast charge at rates up to 350 kW, using the NACS plug. The Terra and Traveler will be capable of bidirectional charging, and the Terra pickup offers two 120 V and one 240 V AC outlets in its 5.5-foot truck bed.&lt;/p&gt;                                                                             &lt;h2&gt;Range extended to 500 miles&lt;/h2&gt; &lt;p&gt;Pure battery-electric Scouts should have up to 350 miles (563 km), but for those who want to adventure a little farther, there will be range-extended versions that use a gasoline-powered generator to top up the battery pack. Such equipped Scouts should be capable of 500 miles (805 km).&lt;/p&gt; &lt;figure class="ars-img-shortcode id-2058206 align-fullwidth"&gt;     &lt;div&gt;                         &lt;img decoding="async" width="3000" height="2000" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Traveler-Concept-5-1.png" class="fullwidth full" alt="A Scout Traveler SUV seen in profile" srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Traveler-Concept-5-1.png 3000w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Traveler-Concept-5-1-300x200.png 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Traveler-Concept-5-1-640x427.png 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Traveler-Concept-5-1-768x512.png 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Traveler-Concept-5-1-1536x1024.png 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Traveler-Concept-5-1-2048x1365.png 2048w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Traveler-Concept-5-1-980x653.png 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Traveler-Concept-5-1-1440x960.png 1440w" sizes="(max-width: 3000px) 100vw, 3000px"&gt;                   &lt;/div&gt;                   &lt;figcaption&gt;           &lt;div class="caption mt-1 inline-flex flex-row items-stretch gap-1 text-lg leading-tight text-gray-300"&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-icon bg-[left_top_5px] w-[10px] shrink-0"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;     &lt;div class="caption-content"&gt;       With looks like these, I think the Traveler will be popular.                &lt;span class="caption-credit mt-2 whitespace-nowrap text-xs"&gt;           Credit:                       Scout Motors                    &lt;/span&gt;           &lt;/div&gt;   &lt;/div&gt;         &lt;/figcaption&gt;             &lt;/figure&gt;  &lt;p&gt;Those miles don't need to be all on paved roads, as off-road performance has been a priority for this new startup. The platform has more than a foot (0.3 m) of ground clearance and can ford water at depths of up to 3 feet (0.9 m). It also has front and rear axles with locking mechanical differentials. The rear axle is a live axle design, and the front anti-roll bar can be disconnected for more wheel travel. It can also fit 35-inch all-terrain tires.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Scout owners should be able to haul stuff, too—the Terra truck boasts up to 10,000 lbs (4,536 kg) of towing capacity, and the Traveler SUV 7,000 lbs (3,175 kg). And both pickup and SUV can carry payloads of up to 2,000 lbs (907 kg).&lt;/p&gt; &lt;div class="ars-lightbox align-fullwidth my-5"&gt;&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img decoding="async" width="1440" height="1080" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Traveler-Concept-6-1440x1080.jpg" class="ars-gallery-image" alt="The front seats of a Scout Traveler SUV" loading="lazy" aria-labelledby="caption-2058205" srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Traveler-Concept-6-1440x1080.jpg 1440w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Traveler-Concept-6-300x225.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Traveler-Concept-6-640x480.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Traveler-Concept-6-768x576.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Traveler-Concept-6-1536x1152.jpg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Traveler-Concept-6-2048x1536.jpg 2048w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Traveler-Concept-6-980x735.jpg 980w" sizes="(max-width: 1440px) 100vw, 1440px"&gt;&lt;figcaption&gt;       You could have a bench seat here if you want. Note all the physical controls on the dashboard.               &lt;div class="ars-gallery-caption-credit"&gt;Credit:                        Scout Motors                   &lt;/div&gt;           &lt;/figcaption&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img decoding="async" width="640" height="427" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Traveler-Concept-8-Split-Tailgate-640x427.jpg" class="ars-gallery-image" alt="The split tailgate of a Scout Traveler SUV, seen open. The glass goes up and the bit with the spare tire opens out to one side." loading="lazy" aria-labelledby="caption-2058204" srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Traveler-Concept-8-Split-Tailgate-640x427.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Traveler-Concept-8-Split-Tailgate-300x200.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Traveler-Concept-8-Split-Tailgate-768x512.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Traveler-Concept-8-Split-Tailgate-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Traveler-Concept-8-Split-Tailgate-2048x1365.jpg 2048w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Traveler-Concept-8-Split-Tailgate-980x653.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Traveler-Concept-8-Split-Tailgate-1440x960.jpg 1440w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px"&gt;&lt;figcaption&gt;       The Traveler has a split tailgate.                &lt;div class="ars-gallery-caption-credit"&gt;Credit:                        Scout Motors                   &lt;/div&gt;           &lt;/figcaption&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img decoding="async" width="640" height="427" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Traveler-Concept-Cabana-Roof-7-640x427.jpg" class="ars-gallery-image" alt="A view of the Scout Traveler's big open roof, seen from its back seat." loading="lazy" aria-labelledby="caption-2058203" srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Traveler-Concept-Cabana-Roof-7-640x427.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Traveler-Concept-Cabana-Roof-7-300x200.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Traveler-Concept-Cabana-Roof-7-768x512.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Traveler-Concept-Cabana-Roof-7-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Traveler-Concept-Cabana-Roof-7-2048x1365.jpg 2048w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Traveler-Concept-Cabana-Roof-7-980x653.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/Scout-Traveler-Concept-Cabana-Roof-7-1440x960.jpg 1440w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px"&gt;&lt;figcaption&gt;       Scout says it will have a range of different roof types that will offer open-air experiences. This is the cabana top, which it says will be the largest roof opening on any SUV.               &lt;div class="ars-gallery-caption-credit"&gt;Credit:                        Scout Motors                   &lt;/div&gt;           &lt;/figcaption&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;&lt;/div&gt;  &lt;p&gt;The Scout name isn't the only comeback, because you'll be given the option of an actual front bench seat. If my research is correct, the last new vehicle to be offered with a front bench seat was the 2013 Chevrolet Impala.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;We can also expect a thoroughly up-to-date electronic architecture inside the car. Scout describes it as a modern zonal architecture (also known as a software-defined vehicle), and it's likely the Terra and Traveler will benefit from VW's $5 billion investment in Rivian, which allows the German automaker access to Rivian's software &lt;a href="https://arstechnica.com/cars/2023/04/whats-going-on-with-volkswagens-software-division/"&gt;after repeated stumbles&lt;/a&gt; at CARIAD, VW's in-house software division.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;If this sounds enticing, &lt;a href="https://arstechnica.com/www.scoutmotors.com"&gt;Scout&lt;/a&gt; has just opened its order books. After leaving a refundable $100 deposit, you can pick whether you want a Terra or Traveler and whether it should be a BEV or range-extended version.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
